# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: iris-go
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:iris-go/go-programming-language] A third-party source-to-source compiler, GopherJS, transpiles Go to JavaScript for front-end web development.
[src:iris-go/go-programming-language] Go was designed at Google in 2007 to improve programming productivity in an era of multicore, networked machines and large codebases.
[src:iris-go/go-programming-language] Its designers were primarily motivated by their shared dislike of C++.
[src:iris-go/go-programming-language] Go was publicly announced in November 2009, and version 1.0 was released in March 2012.
[src:iris-go/go-programming-language] Go is widely used in production at Google and in many other organizations and open-source projects.
[src:iris-go/go-programming-language] In retrospect the Go authors judged Go to be successful due to the overall engineering work around the language, including the runtime support for the language's concurrency feature.
[src:iris-go/go-programming-language] The gopher mascot was introduced in 2009 for the open source launch of the language.
[src:iris-go/go-programming-language] Renée French, who had designed the rabbit mascot for Plan 9, adapted the gopher from an earlier WFMU T-shirt design.
[src:iris-go/go-programming-language] In November 2016, the Go and Go Mono fonts were released by type designers Charles Bigelow and Kris Holmes specifically for use by the Go project.
[src:iris-go/go-programming-language] Go is a humanist sans-serif resembling Lucida Grande, and Go Mono is monospaced.
[src:iris-go/go-programming-language] Both fonts adhere to the WGL4 character set and were designed to be legible with a large x-height and distinct letterforms.
[src:iris-go/go-programming-language] Both Go and Go Mono adhere to the DIN 1450 standard by having a slashed zero, lowercase `i` with a tail, and an uppercase `I` with serifs.
[src:iris-go/go-programming-language] In April 2018, the original logo was redesigned by brand designer Adam Smith.
[src:iris-go/go-programming-language] The new logo is a modern, stylized GO slanting right with trailing streamlines.
[src:iris-go/go-programming-language] The lack of support for generic programming in initial versions of Go drew considerable criticism.
[src:iris-go/go-programming-language] The designers expressed an openness to generic programming and noted that built-in functions *were* in fact type-generic, but are treated as special cases; Pike called this a weakness that might be changed at some point.
[src:iris-go/go-programming-language] The Google team built at least one compiler for an experimental Go dialect with generics, but did not release it.
[src:iris-go/go-programming-language] In August 2018, the Go principal contributors published draft designs for generic programming and error handling and asked users to submit feedback.
[src:iris-go/go-programming-language] However, the error handling proposal was eventually abandoned.
[src:iris-go/go-programming-language] In June 2020, a new draft design document was published that would add the necessary syntax to Go for declaring generic functions and types.
[src:iris-go/go-programming-language] A code translation tool, *go2go*, was provided to allow users to try the new syntax, along with a generics-enabled version of the online Go Playground.
[src:iris-go/go-programming-language] Generics were finally added to Go in version 1.18 on March 15, 2022.
[src:iris-go/go-programming-language] Go 1 guarantees compatibility for the language specification and major parts of the standard library.
[src:iris-go/go-programming-language] All versions up through the current Go 1.26 release have maintained this promise.
[src:iris-go/go-programming-language] Go uses a `go1.[major].[patch]` versioning format, such as `go1.26.0` and each major Go release is supported until there are two newer major releases.
[src:iris-go/go-programming-language] Unlike most software, Go calls the second number in a version the major, i.e., in `go1.26.0` the `26` is the major version.
[src:iris-go/go-programming-language] This is because Go plans to never reach 2.0, prioritizing backwards compatibility over potential breaking changes.
[src:iris-go/go-programming-language] Go is influenced by C (especially the Plan 9 dialect), but with an emphasis on greater simplicity and safety.
[src:iris-go/go-programming-language] Go's syntax includes changes from C aimed at keeping code concise and readable.
[src:iris-go/go-programming-language] A combined declaration/initialization operator was introduced that allows the programmer to write `i := 3` or `s := "Hello, world!"`, without specifying the types of variables used.
[src:iris-go/go-programming-language] This contrasts with C's `int i = 3;` and `char *s = "Hello, world!";` (though since C23 type inference has been supported using `auto`, like C++).
[src:iris-go/go-programming-language] Go also removes the requirement to use parentheses in `if` statement conditions.
[src:iris-go/go-programming-language] Semicolons still terminate statements; but are implicit when the end of a line occurs.
[src:iris-go/go-programming-language] Methods may return multiple values, and returning a `result, err` pair is the conventional way a method indicates an error to its caller in Go.
[src:iris-go/go-programming-language] Go adds literal syntaxes for initializing struct parameters by name and for initializing maps and slices.
[src:iris-go/go-programming-language] As an alternative to C's three-statement `for` loop, Go's `range` expressions allow concise iteration over arrays, slices, strings, maps, and channels.
[src:iris-go/go-programming-language] Go has a number of built-in types, including numeric ones (`byte`, `int64`, `float32`, etc.), Booleans, and byte strings (`string`).
[src:iris-go/go-programming-language] Strings are immutable; built-in operators and keywords (rather than functions) provide concatenation, comparison, and UTF-8 encoding/decoding.
[src:iris-go/go-programming-language] Record types can be defined with the `struct` keyword.
[src:iris-go/go-programming-language] Note that `byte` is an alias for `uint8` and `rune` is an alias for `int32`.
[src:iris-go/go-programming-language] For each type `T` and each non-negative integer constant `n`, there is an array type denoted `[n]T`; arrays of differing lengths are thus of different types.
[src:iris-go/go-programming-language] Dynamic arrays are available as "slices", denoted `[]T` for some type `T` (compare to other languages like C/C++ and Java, where instead the arrays are denoted `T[]`) These have a length and a *capacity* specifying when new memory needs to be allocated to expand the array.
[src:iris-go/go-programming-language] Several slices may share their underlying memory.
[src:iris-go/go-programming-language] For a pair of types `K`, `V`, the type `map[K]V` is the type mapping type-`K` keys to type-`V` values, which can be thought of as equivalent to `Map<K, V>` in other languages.
[src:iris-go/go-programming-language] The Go Programming Language specification does not give any performance guarantees or implementation requirements for map types, though it is usually implemented as a hash table (equivalent to `HashMap<K, V>` in other languages).
[src:iris-go/go-programming-language] Hash tables are built into the language, with special syntax and built-in functions.
[src:iris-go/go-programming-language] `chan T` is a *channel* that allows sending values of type `T` between concurrent Go processes.
[src:iris-go/go-programming-language] Aside from its support for interfaces, Go's type system is nominal: the `type` keyword can be used to define a new *named type*, which is distinct from other named types that have the same layout (in the case of a `struct`, the same members in the same order).
[src:iris-go/go-programming-language] Some conversions between types (e.g., between the various integer types) are pre-defined and adding a new type may define additional conversions, but conversions between named types must always be invoked explicitly.
[src:iris-go/go-programming-language] With this type definition, `ipv4addr(x)` interprets the `uint32` value `x` as an IP address.
[src:iris-go/go-programming-language] Simply assigning `x` to a variable of type `ipv4addr` is a type error.
[src:iris-go/go-programming-language] Any named type has a method set associated with it.
[src:iris-go/go-programming-language] Due to nominal typing, this method definition adds a method to `ipv4addr`, but not on `uint32`.
[src:iris-go/go-programming-language] While methods have special definition and call syntax, there is no distinct method type.
[src:iris-go/go-programming-language] Go provides two features that replace class inheritance.
[src:iris-go/go-programming-language] The first is *embedding*, which can be viewed as an automated form of composition.
[src:iris-go/go-programming-language] The second are its *interfaces*, which provides runtime polymorphism.
[src:iris-go/go-programming-language] Interfaces are a class of types and provide a limited form of structural typing in the otherwise nominal type system of Go.
[src:iris-go/go-programming-language] An object which is of an interface type is also of another type, much like C++ objects being simultaneously of a base and derived class.
[src:iris-go/go-programming-language] The design of Go interfaces was inspired by protocols from the Smalltalk programming language.
[src:iris-go/go-programming-language] Multiple sources use the term duck typing when describing Go interfaces.
[src:iris-go/go-programming-language] Although the term duck typing is not precisely defined and therefore not wrong, it usually implies that type conformance is not statically checked.
[src:iris-go/go-programming-language] Because conformance to a Go interface is checked statically by the Go compiler (except when performing a type assertion), the Go authors prefer the term *structural typing*.
[src:iris-go/go-programming-language] The definition of an interface type lists required methods by name and type.
[src:iris-go/go-programming-language] Any object of type T for which functions exist matching all the required methods of interface type I is an object of type I as well.
[src:iris-go/go-programming-language] The definition of type T need not (and cannot) identify type I.
[src:iris-go/go-programming-language] then both a `Square` and a `Circle` are implicitly a `Shape` and can be assigned to a `Shape`-typed variable.
[src:iris-go/go-programming-language] In formal language, Go's interface system provides structural rather than nominal typing.
[src:iris-go/go-programming-language] Interfaces can embed other interfaces with the effect of creating a combined interface that is satisfied by exactly the types that implement the embedded interface and any methods that the newly defined interface adds.
[src:iris-go/go-programming-language] The Go standard library uses interfaces to provide genericity in several places, including the input/output system that is based on the concepts of `Reader` and `Writer`.
[src:iris-go/go-programming-language] Besides calling methods via interfaces, Go allows converting interface values to other types with a run-time type check.
[src:iris-go/go-programming-language] The *empty interface* `interface{}` is an important base case because it can refer to an item of *any* concrete type.
[src:iris-go/go-programming-language] It is similar to the `Object` class in Java or C# or `void*` in C or `Any` in C++ and Rust and is satisfied by any type, including built-in types like `int`.
[src:iris-go/go-programming-language] Code using the empty interface cannot simply call methods (or built-in operators) on the referred-to object, but it can store the `interface{}` value, try to convert it to a more useful type via a type assertion or type switch, or inspect it with Go's `reflect` package.
[src:iris-go/go-programming-language] Because `interface{}` can refer to any value, it is a limited way to escape the restrictions of static typing, like `void*` in C but with additional run-time type checks.
[src:iris-go/go-programming-language] The `interface{}` type can be used to model structured data of any arbitrary schema in Go, such as JSON or YAML data, by representing it as a `map[string]interface{}` (map of string to empty interface).
[src:iris-go/go-programming-language] This recursively describes data in the form of a dictionary with string keys and values of any type.
[src:iris-go/go-programming-language] Interface values are implemented using pointer to data and a second pointer to run-time type information.
[src:iris-go/go-programming-language] Like some other types implemented using pointers in Go, interface values are `nil` if uninitialized.
[src:iris-go/go-programming-language] Since version 1.18, Go supports generic code using parameterized types.
[src:iris-go/go-programming-language] Functions and types now have the ability to be generic using type parameters.
[src:iris-go/go-programming-language] These type parameters are specified within square brackets, right after the function or type name.
[src:iris-go/go-programming-language] The compiler transforms the generic function or type into non-generic by substituting *type arguments* for the type parameters provided, either explicitly by the user or type inference by the compiler.
[src:iris-go/go-programming-language] This transformation process is referred to as type instantiation.
[src:iris-go/go-programming-language] Interfaces now can define a set of types (known as type set) using `|` (Union) operator, as well as a set of methods.
[src:iris-go/go-programming-language] These changes were made to support type constraints in generics code.
[src:iris-go/go-programming-language] For a generic function or type, a constraint can be thought of as the type of the type argument: a meta-type.
[src:iris-go/go-programming-language] This new `~T` syntax will be the first use of `~` as a token in Go.
[src:iris-go/go-programming-language] `~T` means the set of all types whose underlying type is `T`.
[src:iris-go/go-programming-language] Go uses the `iota` identifier to create enumerated constants.
[src:iris-go/go-programming-language] In Go's package system, each package has a path (e.g., `"compress/bzip2"` or `"golang.org/x/net/html"`) and a name (e.g., `bzip2` or `html`).
[src:iris-go/go-programming-language] By default other packages' definitions must *always* be prefixed with the other package's name.
[src:iris-go/go-programming-language] However the name used can be changed from the package name, and if imported as `_`, then no package prefix is required.
[src:iris-go/go-programming-language] Only the *capitalized* names from other packages are accessible: `io.Reader` is public but `bzip2.reader` is not.
[src:iris-go/go-programming-language] The Go language has built-in facilities, as well as library support, for writing concurrent programs.
[src:iris-go/go-programming-language] The runtime is asynchronous: program execution that performs, for example, a network read will be suspended until data is available to process, allowing other parts of the program to perform other work.
[src:iris-go/go-programming-language] This is built into the runtime and does not require any changes in program code.
[src:iris-go/go-programming-language] The go runtime also automatically schedules concurrent operations (goroutines) across multiple CPUs; this can achieve parallelism for a properly written program.
[src:iris-go/go-programming-language] The primary concurrency construct is the *goroutine*, a type of green thread.
[src:iris-go/go-programming-language] A function call prefixed with the `go` keyword starts a function in a new goroutine.
[src:iris-go/go-programming-language] While a standard library package featuring most of the classical concurrency control structures (mutex locks, etc.) is available, idiomatic concurrent programs instead prefer *channels*, which send messages between goroutines.
[src:iris-go/go-programming-language] Optional buffers store messages in FIFO order and allow sending goroutines to proceed before their messages are received.
[src:iris-go/go-programming-language] Channels are typed, so that a channel of type `chan T` can only be used to transfer messages of type `T`.
[src:iris-go/go-programming-language] Special syntax is used to operate on them; `<-ch` is an expression that causes the executing goroutine to block until a value comes in over the channel `ch`, while `ch <- x` sends the value `x` (possibly blocking until another goroutine receives the value).
[src:iris-go/go-programming-language] The built-in `switch`-like `select` statement can be used to implement non-blocking communication on multiple channels; see below for an example.
[src:iris-go/go-programming-language] Go has a memory model describing how goroutines must use channels or other operations to safely share data.
[src:iris-go/go-programming-language] The existence of channels does not by itself set Go apart from actor model-style concurrent languages like Erlang, where messages are addressed directly to actors (corresponding to goroutines).
[src:iris-go/go-programming-language] In the actor model, channels are themselves actors, therefore addressing a channel just means to address an actor.
[src:iris-go/go-programming-language] The actor style can be simulated in Go by maintaining a one-to-one correspondence between goroutines and channels, but the language allows multiple goroutines to share a channel or a single goroutine to send and receive on multiple channels.
[src:iris-go/go-programming-language] From these tools one can build concurrent constructs like worker pools, pipelines (in which, say, a file is decompressed and parsed as it downloads), background calls with timeout, "fan-out" parallel calls to a set of services, and others.
[src:iris-go/go-programming-language] Channels have also found uses further from the usual notion of interprocess communication, like serving as a concurrency-safe list of recycled buffers, implementing coroutines (which helped inspire the name *goroutine*), and implementing iterators.
[src:iris-go/go-programming-language] Concurrency-related structural conventions of Go (channels and alternative channel inputs) are derived from Tony Hoare's communicating sequential processes model.
[src:iris-go/go-programming-language] Unlike previous concurrent programming languages such as Occam or Limbo (a language on which Go co-designer Rob Pike worked), Go does not provide any built-in notion of safe or verifiable concurrency.
[src:iris-go/go-programming-language] While the communicating-processes model is favored in Go, it is not the only one: all goroutines in a program share a single address space.
[src:iris-go/go-programming-language] This means that mutable objects and pointers can be shared between goroutines; see § Lack of data race safety, below.
[src:iris-go/go-programming-language] Although Go's concurrency features are not aimed primarily at parallel processing, they can be used to program shared-memory multi-processor machines.
[src:iris-go/go-programming-language] Various studies have been done into the effectiveness of this approach.
[src:iris-go/go-programming-language] One of these studies compared the size (in lines of code) and speed of programs written by a seasoned programmer not familiar with the language and corrections to these programs by a Go expert (from Google's development team), doing the same for Chapel, Cilk and Intel TBB.
[src:iris-go/go-programming-language] The study found that the non-expert tended to write divide-and-conquer algorithms with one `go` statement per recursion, while the expert wrote distribute-work-synchronize programs using one goroutine per processor core.
[src:iris-go/go-programming-language] The expert's programs were usually faster, but also longer.
[src:iris-go/go-programming-language] Go's approach to concurrency can be summarized as "don't communicate by sharing memory; share memory by communicating".
[src:iris-go/go-programming-language] There are no restrictions on how goroutines access shared data, making data races possible.
[src:iris-go/go-programming-language] Specifically, unless a program explicitly synchronizes via channels or other means, writes from one goroutine might be partly, entirely, or not at all visible to another, often with no guarantees about ordering of writes.
[src:iris-go/go-programming-language] Furthermore, Go's *internal data structures* like interface values, slice headers, hash tables, and string headers are not immune to data races, so type and memory safety can be violated in multithreaded programs that modify shared instances of those types without synchronization.
[src:iris-go/go-programming-language] Instead of language support, safe concurrent programming thus relies on conventions; for example, Chisnall recommends an idiom called "aliases xor mutable", meaning that passing a mutable value (or pointer) over a channel signals a transfer of ownership over the value to its receiver.
[src:iris-go/go-programming-language] The gc toolchain has an optional data race detector that can check for unsynchronized access to shared memory during runtime since version 1.1, additionally a best-effort race detector is also included by default since version 1.6 of the gc runtime for access to the `map` data type.
[src:iris-go/go-programming-language] The linker in the gc toolchain creates statically linked binaries by default; therefore all Go binaries include the Go runtime.
[src:iris-go/go-programming-language] Go deliberately omits certain features common in other languages, including (implementation) inheritance, assertions, pointer arithmetic, implicit type conversions, untagged unions, and tagged unions.
[src:iris-go/go-programming-language] The designers added only those facilities that all three agreed on.
[src:iris-go/go-programming-language] Of the omitted language features, the designers explicitly argue against assertions and pointer arithmetic, while defending the choice to omit type inheritance as giving a more useful language, encouraging instead the use of interfaces to achieve dynamic dispatch and composition to reuse code.
[src:iris-go/go-programming-language] Exception handling was initially omitted in Go due to lack of a "design that gives value proportionate to the complexity".
[src:iris-go/go-programming-language] An exception-like `panic`/`recover` mechanism that avoids the usual `try-catch` control structure was proposed and released in the March 30, 2010 snapshot.
[src:iris-go/go-programming-language] The Go authors advise using it for unrecoverable errors such as those that should halt an entire program or server request, or as a shortcut to propagate errors up the stack within a package.
[src:iris-go/go-programming-language] Across package boundaries, Go includes a canonical error type, and multi-value returns using this type are the standard idiom.
[src:iris-go/go-programming-language] It also includes profiling and debugging support, fuzzing capabilities to detect bugs, runtime instrumentation (for example, to track garbage collection pauses), and a data race detector.
[src:iris-go/go-programming-language] Another tool maintained by the Go team but is not included in Go distributions is `gopls`, a language server that provides IDE features such as intelligent code completion to Language Server Protocol compatible editors.
[src:iris-go/go-programming-language] An ecosystem of third-party tools adds to the standard distribution, such as `gocode`, which enables code autocompletion in many text editors, `goimports`, which automatically adds/removes package imports as needed, and `errcheck`, which detects code that might unintentionally ignore errors.
[src:iris-go/go-programming-language] where "fmt" is the package for *formatted I/O*, similar to C's <stdio.h> or C++ <print>.
[src:iris-go/go-programming-language] The following simple program demonstrates Go's concurrency features to implement an asynchronous program.
[src:iris-go/go-programming-language] It launches two lightweight threads ("goroutines"): one waits for the user to type some text, while the other implements a timeout.
[src:iris-go/go-programming-language] The select statement waits for either of these goroutines to send a message to the main routine, and acts on the first message to arrive (example adapted from David Chisnall's book).
[src:iris-go/go-programming-language] The testing package provides support for automated testing of go packages.
[src:iris-go/go-programming-language] It is possible to run tests in parallel.
[src:iris-go/go-programming-language] The net/http package provides support for creating web applications.
[src:iris-go/go-programming-language] This example would show "Hello world!" when localhost:8080 is visited.
[src:iris-go/go-programming-language] Go has found widespread adoption in various domains due to its robust standard library and ease of use.
[src:iris-go/go-programming-language] The interface system, and the deliberate omission of inheritance, were praised by Michele Simionato, who likened these characteristics to those of Standard ML, calling it "a shame that no popular language has followed [this] particular route".
[src:iris-go/go-programming-language] By June 2015, its ranking had dropped to below 50th in the index, placing it lower than COBOL and Fortran.
[src:iris-go/go-programming-language] But as of January 2017, its ranking had surged to 13th, indicating significant growth in popularity and adoption.
[src:iris-go/go-programming-language] Go was again awarded TIOBE Programming Language of the Year in 2016.
[src:iris-go/go-programming-language] The evaluation got a rebuttal from the Go development team.
[src:iris-go/go-programming-language] On November 10, 2009, the day of the general release of the language, Francis McCabe, developer of the Go! programming language (note the exclamation point), requested a name change of Google's language to prevent confusion with his language, which he had spent 10 years developing.
[src:iris-go/model-view-controller] Traditionally used for desktop graphical user interfaces (GUIs), this pattern became popular for designing web applications.
[src:iris-go/model-view-controller] Popular programming languages have MVC frameworks that facilitate the implementation of the pattern.
[src:iris-go/model-view-controller] One of the seminal insights in the early development of graphical user interfaces, MVC became one of the first approaches to describe and implement software constructs in terms of their responsibilities.
[src:iris-go/model-view-controller] Trygve Reenskaug created MVC while working on Smalltalk-79 as a visiting scientist at the Xerox Palo Alto Research Center (PARC) in the late 1970s.
[src:iris-go/model-view-controller] He wanted a pattern that could be used to structure any program where users interact with a large, convoluted data set.
[src:iris-go/model-view-controller] His design initially had four parts: Model, view, thing, and editor.
[src:iris-go/model-view-controller] After discussing it with the other Smalltalk developers, he and the rest of the group settled on model, view, and controller instead.
[src:iris-go/model-view-controller] In their final design, a model represents some part of the program purely and intuitively.
[src:iris-go/model-view-controller] A view is a visual representation of a model, retrieving data from the model to display to the user and passing requests back and forth between the user and the model.
[src:iris-go/model-view-controller] A controller is an organizational part of the user interface that lays out and coordinates multiple Views on the screen, and which receives user input and sends the appropriate messages to its underlying Views.
[src:iris-go/model-view-controller] This design also includes an Editor as a specialized kind of controller used to modify a particular view, and which is created through that view.
[src:iris-go/model-view-controller] Smalltalk-80 supports a version of MVC that evolved from this one.
[src:iris-go/model-view-controller] It provides abstract `view` and `controller` classes as well as various concrete subclasses of each that represent different generic widgets.
[src:iris-go/model-view-controller] In this scheme, a `View` represents some way of displaying information to the user, and a `controller` represents some way for the user to interact with a `view`.
[src:iris-go/model-view-controller] A `view` is also coupled to a model object, but the structure of that object is left up to the application programmer.
[src:iris-go/model-view-controller] The Smalltalk-80 environment also includes an "MVC Inspector", a development tool for viewing the structure of a given model, view, and controller side-by-side.
[src:iris-go/model-view-controller] In 1988, an article in *The Journal of Object Technology* (JOT) by two ex-PARC employees presented MVC as a general "programming paradigm and methodology" for Smalltalk-80 developers.
[src:iris-go/model-view-controller] However, their scheme differed from both Reenskaug et al.'s and that presented by the Smalltalk-80 reference books.
[src:iris-go/model-view-controller] They defined a view as covering any graphical concern, with a controller being a more abstract, generally invisible object that receives user input and interacts with one or many views and only one model.
[src:iris-go/model-view-controller] The MVC pattern subsequently evolved, giving rise to variants such as hierarchical model–view–controller (HMVC), model–view–adapter (MVA), model–view–presenter (MVP), model–view–viewmodel (MVVM), and others that adapted MVC to different contexts.
[src:iris-go/model-view-controller] The use of the MVC pattern in web applications grew after the introduction of NeXT's WebObjects in 1996, which was originally written in Objective-C (that borrowed heavily from Smalltalk) and helped enforce MVC principles.
[src:iris-go/model-view-controller] Later, the MVC pattern became popular with Java developers when WebObjects was ported to Java.
[src:iris-go/model-view-controller] Later frameworks for Java, such as Spring (released in October 2002), continued the strong bond between Java and MVC.
[src:iris-go/model-view-controller] This is close to the approach taken by the Ruby on Rails web application framework (August 2004), which has the client send requests to the server via an in-browser view, these requests are handled by a controller on the server, and the controller communicates with the appropriate model objects.
[src:iris-go/model-view-controller] The Django framework (July 2005, for Python) put forward a similar "model-template-view" (MTV) take on the pattern, in which a view retrieves data from models and passes it to templates for display.
[src:iris-go/model-view-controller] Both Rails and Django debuted with a strong emphasis on rapid deployment, which increased MVC's popularity outside the traditional enterprise environment in which it has long been popular.
[src:iris-go/model-view-controller] It is the application's dynamic data structure, independent of the user interface.
[src:iris-go/model-view-controller] It directly manages the data, logic and rules of the application.
[src:iris-go/model-view-controller] In Smalltalk-80, the design of a model type is left entirely to the programmer.
[src:iris-go/model-view-controller] With WebObjects, Rails, and Django, a model type typically represents a table in the application's database.
[src:iris-go/model-view-controller] The model is essential for keeping the data organized and consistent.
[src:iris-go/model-view-controller] It ensures that the application's data behaves according to the defined rules and logic.
[src:iris-go/model-view-controller] Any representation of information such as a chart, diagram or table.
[src:iris-go/model-view-controller] Multiple views of the same information are possible, such as a bar chart for management and a tabular view for accountants.
[src:iris-go/model-view-controller] In Smalltalk-80, a view is just a visual representation of a model, and does not handle user input.
[src:iris-go/model-view-controller] With WebObjects, a view represents a complete user interface element such as a menu or button, and does receive input from the user.
[src:iris-go/model-view-controller] In both Smalltalk-80 and WebObjects, however, views are meant to be general-purpose and composable.
[src:iris-go/model-view-controller] With Rails and Django, the role of the view is played by HTML templates, so in their scheme a view specifies an in-browser user interface rather than representing a user interface widget directly.
[src:iris-go/model-view-controller] (Django opts to call this kind of object a "template" in light of this.) This approach puts relatively less emphasis on small, composable views; a typical Rails view has a one-to-one relationship with a controller action.
[src:iris-go/model-view-controller] Smalltalk-80 views communicate with both a model and a controller, whereas with WebObjects, a view talks only to a controller, which then talks to a model.
[src:iris-go/model-view-controller] With Rails and Django, a view/template is used by a controller/view when preparing a response to the client.
[src:iris-go/model-view-controller] Accepts input and converts it to commands for the model or view.
[src:iris-go/model-view-controller] A Smalltalk-80 controller handles user input events, such as button presses or mouse movement.
[src:iris-go/model-view-controller] At any given time, each controller has one associated view and model, although one model object may hear from many different controllers.
[src:iris-go/model-view-controller] Only one controller, the "active" controller, receives user input at any given time; a global window manager object is responsible for setting the current active controller.
[src:iris-go/model-view-controller] If user input prompts a change in a model, the controller will signal the model to change, but the model is then responsible for telling its views to update.
[src:iris-go/model-view-controller] In WebObjects, the views handle user input, and the controller mediates between the views and the models.
[src:iris-go/model-view-controller] There may be only one controller per application, or one controller per window.
[src:iris-go/model-view-controller] Much of the application-specific logic is found in the controller.
[src:iris-go/model-view-controller] In Rails, requests arriving at the on-server application from the client are sent to a "router", which maps the request to a specific method of a specific controller.
[src:iris-go/model-view-controller] Within that method, the controller interacts with the request data and any relevant model objects and prepares a response using a view.
[src:iris-go/model-view-controller] Conventionally, each view has an associated controller; for example, if the application had a `client` view, it would typically have an associated `Clients` controller as well.
[src:iris-go/model-view-controller] However, developers are free to make other kinds of controllers if they wish.
[src:iris-go/model-view-controller] Django calls the object playing this role a "view" instead of a controller.
[src:iris-go/model-view-controller] A Django view is a function that receives a web request and returns a web response.
[src:iris-go/model-view-controller] It may use templates to create the response.
[src:iris-go/model-view-controller] As with other software patterns, MVC expresses the "core of the solution" to a problem while allowing it to be adapted for each system.
[src:iris-go/model-view-controller] Particular MVC designs can vary significantly from the traditional description here.
[src:iris-go/model-view-controller] As Alan Kay wrote in 2003, the original motivation behind the MVC was to allow creation of a graphical interface for any object.
[src:iris-go/model-view-controller] That was outlined in detail in Richard Pawson's book *Naked Objects*.
[src:iris-go/model-view-controller] Although originally developed for desktop computing, MVC has been widely adopted as a design for World Wide Web applications in major programming languages.
[src:iris-go/model-view-controller] Several web frameworks have been created that enforce the pattern.
[src:iris-go/model-view-controller] These software frameworks vary in their interpretations, mainly in the way that the MVC responsibilities are divided between the client and server.
[src:iris-go/model-view-controller] Early MVC frameworks took a thin client approach that placed almost the entire model, view and controller logic on the server.
[src:iris-go/model-view-controller] In this approach, the client sends hyperlink requests or form submissions to the controller and then receives a complete and updated web page (or other document) from the view; the model exists entirely on the server.
[src:iris-go/model-view-controller] Later frameworks have allowed the MVC components to execute partly on the client, using Ajax to synchronize data.
