[src:iris-go/routing] In packet switching networks, routing is the higher-level decision-making that directs network packets from their source toward their destination through intermediate network nodes by specific packet forwarding mechanisms.
[src:iris-go/routing] Packet forwarding is the transit of network packets from one network interface to another.
[src:iris-go/routing] Intermediate nodes are typically network hardware devices such as routers, gateways, firewalls, or switches.
[src:iris-go/routing] General-purpose computers also forward packets and perform routing, although they have no specially optimized hardware for the task.
[src:iris-go/routing] The routing process usually directs forwarding on the basis of routing tables.
[src:iris-go/routing] Routing tables maintain a record of the routes to various network destinations.
[src:iris-go/routing] Routing tables may be specified by an administrator, learned by observing network traffic or built with the assistance of routing protocols.
[src:iris-go/routing] Routing, in a narrower sense of the term, often refers to IP routing and is contrasted with bridging.
[src:iris-go/routing] IP routing assumes that network addresses are structured and that similar addresses imply proximity within the network.
[src:iris-go/routing] Structured addresses allow a single routing table entry to represent the route to a group of devices.
[src:iris-go/routing] In large networks, structured addressing (routing, in the narrow sense) outperforms unstructured addressing (bridging).
[src:iris-go/routing] Routing has become the dominant form of addressing on the Internet.
[src:iris-go/routing] Bridging is still widely used within local area networks.
[src:iris-go/routing] Unicast is the dominant form of message delivery on the Internet.
[src:iris-go/routing] This article focuses on unicast routing algorithms.
[src:iris-go/routing] With static routing, small networks may use manually configured routing tables.
[src:iris-go/routing] Larger networks have complex topologies that can change rapidly, making the manual construction of routing tables unfeasible.
[src:iris-go/routing] Nevertheless, most of the public switched telephone network (PSTN) uses pre-computed routing tables, with fallback routes if the most direct route becomes blocked (see routing in the PSTN).
[src:iris-go/routing] Dynamic routing attempts to solve this problem by constructing routing tables automatically, based on information carried by routing protocols, allowing the network to act nearly autonomously in avoiding network failures and blockages.
[src:iris-go/routing] Examples of dynamic-routing protocols and algorithms include Routing Information Protocol (RIP), Open Shortest Path First (OSPF) and Enhanced Interior Gateway Routing Protocol (EIGRP).
[src:iris-go/routing] Distance vector algorithms use the Bellman–Ford algorithm.
[src:iris-go/routing] This approach assigns a *cost* number to each of the links between each node in the network.
[src:iris-go/routing] Nodes send information from point A to point B via the path that results in the lowest *total cost* (i.e., the sum of the costs of the links between the nodes used).
[src:iris-go/routing] When a node first starts, it only knows of its immediate neighbors and the direct cost involved in reaching them.
[src:iris-go/routing] The neighboring nodes examine this information and compare it to what they already know; anything that represents an improvement on what they already have, they insert in their own table.
[src:iris-go/routing] Over time, all the nodes in the network discover the best next hop and total cost for all destinations.
[src:iris-go/routing] When a network node goes down, any nodes that used it as their next hop discard the entry and convey the updated routing information to all adjacent nodes, which in turn repeat the process.
[src:iris-go/routing] Eventually, all the nodes in the network receive the updates and discover new paths to all the destinations that do not involve the down node.
[src:iris-go/routing] When applying link-state algorithms, a graphical map of the network is the fundamental data used for each node.
[src:iris-go/routing] To produce its map, each node floods the entire network with information about the other nodes it can connect to.
[src:iris-go/routing] Each node then independently assembles this information into a map.
[src:iris-go/routing] Using this map, each router independently determines the least-cost path from itself to every other node using a standard shortest paths algorithm such as Dijkstra's algorithm.
[src:iris-go/routing] The result is a tree graph rooted at the current node, such that the path through the tree from the root to any other node is the least-cost path to that node.
[src:iris-go/routing] This tree then serves to construct the routing table, which specifies the best next hop to get from the current node to any other node.
[src:iris-go/routing] A link-state routing algorithm optimized for mobile ad hoc networks is the optimized Link State Routing Protocol (OLSR).
[src:iris-go/routing] OLSR is proactive; it uses Hello and Topology Control (TC) messages to discover and disseminate link-state information through the mobile ad hoc network.
[src:iris-go/routing] Using Hello messages, each node discovers 2-hop neighbor information and elects a set of *multipoint relays* (MPRs).
[src:iris-go/routing] MPRs distinguish OLSR from other link-state routing protocols.
[src:iris-go/routing] Distance vector and link-state routing are both intra-domain routing protocols.
[src:iris-go/routing] They are used inside an autonomous system, but not between autonomous systems.
[src:iris-go/routing] Both of these routing protocols become intractable in large networks and cannot be used in inter-domain routing.
[src:iris-go/routing] Distance vector routing is subject to instability if there are more than a few hops in the domain.
[src:iris-go/routing] Link-state routing needs significant resources to calculate routing tables.
[src:iris-go/routing] It also creates heavy traffic due to flooding.
[src:iris-go/routing] Path-vector routing is used for inter-domain routing.
[src:iris-go/routing] It is similar to distance vector routing.
[src:iris-go/routing] Path-vector routing assumes that one node (there can be many) in each autonomous system acts on behalf of the entire autonomous system.
[src:iris-go/routing] This node is called the *speaker node.* The speaker node creates a routing table and advertises it to neighboring speaker nodes in neighboring autonomous systems.
[src:iris-go/routing] The idea is the same as distance vector routing, except that only speaker nodes in each autonomous system can communicate with each other.
[src:iris-go/routing] The speaker node advertises the path, not the metric, of the nodes in its autonomous system or other autonomous systems.
[src:iris-go/routing] The path-vector routing algorithm is similar to the distance vector algorithm in the sense that each border router advertises the destinations it can reach to its neighboring router.
[src:iris-go/routing] However, instead of advertising networks in terms of a destination and the distance to that destination, networks are advertised as destination addresses and path descriptions to reach those destinations.
[src:iris-go/routing] The path, expressed in terms of the domains (or confederations) traversed so far, is carried in a special path attribute that records the sequence of routing domains through which the reachability information has passed.
[src:iris-go/routing] A route is defined as a pairing between a destination and the attributes of the path to that destination, thus the name, path-vector routing.
[src:iris-go/routing] The routers receive a vector that contains paths to a set of destinations.
[src:iris-go/routing] Path selection involves applying a routing metric to multiple routes to select (or predict) the best route.
[src:iris-go/routing] Most routing algorithms use only one network path at a time.
[src:iris-go/routing] Multipath routing and specifically equal-cost multi-path routing techniques enable the use of multiple alternative paths.
[src:iris-go/routing] In computer networking, the metric is computed by a routing algorithm, and can cover information such as bandwidth, network delay, hop count, path cost, load, maximum transmission unit, reliability, and communication cost.
[src:iris-go/routing] The routing table stores only the best possible routes, while link-state or topological databases may store all other information as well.
[src:iris-go/routing] *Metric*: When comparing routes learned via the same routing protocol, a lower metric is preferred.
[src:iris-go/routing] Metrics cannot be compared between routes learned from different routing protocols.
[src:iris-go/routing] *Administrative distance*: When comparing route table entries from different sources, such as different routing protocols and static configuration, a lower administrative distance indicates a more reliable source and thus a preferred route.
[src:iris-go/routing] Because a routing metric is specific to a given routing protocol, multi-protocol routers must use some external heuristic to select between routes learned from different routing protocols.
[src:iris-go/routing] Cisco routers, for example, attribute a value known as the administrative distance to each route, where smaller administrative distances indicate routes learned from a protocol assumed to be more reliable.
[src:iris-go/routing] A local administrator can set up host-specific routes that provide more control over network usage, permit testing, and better overall security.
[src:iris-go/routing] This is useful for debugging network connections or routing tables.
[src:iris-go/routing] In some small systems, a single central device decides ahead of time the complete path of every packet.
[src:iris-go/routing] In some other small systems, whichever edge device injects a packet into the network decides ahead of time the complete path of that particular packet.
[src:iris-go/routing] In either case, the route-planning device needs to know a lot of information about what devices are connected to the network and how they are connected to each other.
[src:iris-go/routing] Once it has this information, it can use an algorithm such as A* search algorithm to find the best path.
[src:iris-go/routing] In high-speed systems, there are so many packets transmitted every second that it is infeasible for a single device to calculate the complete path for each and every packet.
[src:iris-go/routing] Early high-speed systems dealt with this with circuit switching by setting up a path once for the first packet between some source and some destination; later packets between that same source and that same destination continue to follow the same path without recalculating until the circuit teardown.
[src:iris-go/routing] Later high-speed systems inject packets into the network without any one device ever calculating a complete path for packets.
[src:iris-go/routing] In large systems, there are so many connections between devices, and those connections change so frequently, that it is infeasible for any one device to even know how all the devices are connected to each other, much less calculate a complete path through them.
[src:iris-go/routing] Such systems generally use next-hop routing.
[src:iris-go/routing] Most systems use a deterministic dynamic routing algorithm.
[src:iris-go/routing] When a device chooses a path to a particular final destination, that device always chooses the same path to that destination until it receives information that makes it think some other path is better.
[src:iris-go/routing] A few routing algorithms do not use a deterministic algorithm to find the best link for a packet to get from its original source to its final destination.
[src:iris-go/routing] Instead, to avoid congestion hot spots in packet systems, a few algorithms use a randomized algorithm—Valiant's paradigm—that routes a path to a randomly picked intermediate destination, and from there to its true final destination.
[src:iris-go/routing] In many early telephone switches, a randomizer was often used to select the start of a path through a multistage switching fabric.
[src:iris-go/routing] Depending on the application for which path selection is performed, different metrics can be used.
[src:iris-go/routing] For example, for web requests, one can use minimum latency paths to minimize web page load time, or for bulk data transfers, one can choose the least utilized path to balance load across the network and increase throughput.
[src:iris-go/routing] A popular path selection objective is to reduce the average completion times of traffic flows and the total network bandwidth consumption.
[src:iris-go/routing] Recently, a path selection metric was proposed that computes the total number of bytes scheduled on the edges per path as a selection metric.
[src:iris-go/routing] An empirical analysis of several path selection metrics, including this new proposal, has been made available.
[src:iris-go/routing] In some networks, routing is complicated by the fact that no single entity is responsible for selecting paths; instead, multiple entities are involved in selecting paths or even parts of a single path.
[src:iris-go/routing] Complications or inefficiency can result if these entities choose paths to optimize their own objectives, which may conflict with the objectives of other participants.
[src:iris-go/routing] A classic example involves traffic in a road system, in which each driver picks a path that minimizes their travel time.
[src:iris-go/routing] With such routing, the equilibrium routes can be longer than optimal for all drivers.
[src:iris-go/routing] In particular, Braess's paradox shows that adding a new road can *lengthen* travel times for all drivers.
[src:iris-go/routing] In a single-agent model used, for example, for routing automated guided vehicles (AGVs) on a terminal, reservations are made for each vehicle to prevent simultaneous use of the same part of an infrastructure.
[src:iris-go/routing] This approach is also referred to as context-aware routing.
[src:iris-go/routing] The Internet is partitioned into autonomous systems (ASs) such as internet service providers (ISPs), each of which controls routes involving its network.
[src:iris-go/routing] First, AS-level paths are selected via the BGP protocol that produces a sequence of ASs through which packets flow.
[src:iris-go/routing] Each AS may have multiple paths, offered by neighboring ASs, from which to choose.
[src:iris-go/routing] These routing decisions often correlate with business relationships with these neighboring ASs, which may be unrelated to path quality or latency.
[src:iris-go/routing] Second, once an AS-level path has been selected, there are often multiple corresponding router-level paths to choose from.
[src:iris-go/routing] This is due, in part, because two ISPs may be connected through multiple connections.
[src:iris-go/routing] In choosing the single router-level path, it is common practice for each ISP to employ hot-potato routing: sending traffic along the path that minimizes the distance through the ISP's own network—even if that path lengthens the total distance to the destination.
[src:iris-go/routing] For example, consider two ISPs, *A* and *B*.
[src:iris-go/routing] Each has a presence in New York, connected by a fast link with latency 5 ms—and each has a presence in London connected by a 5 ms link.
[src:iris-go/routing] Suppose both ISPs have trans-Atlantic links that connect their two networks, but *A*'s link has latency 100 ms and *B*'s has latency 120 ms.
[src:iris-go/routing] When routing a message from a source in *A*'s London network to a destination in *B*'s New York network, *A* may choose to immediately send the message to *B* in London.
[src:iris-go/routing] This saves *A* the work of sending it along an expensive trans-Atlantic link, but causes the message to experience latency 125 ms when the other route would have been 20 ms faster.
[src:iris-go/routing] Additionally, a similar routing challenge can be observed in cellular networks, where different packets are destined for various endpoints, and each link exhibits varying spectral efficiency.
[src:iris-go/routing] In this context, the selection of the *optimal* path involves considering latency and packet error rate.
[src:iris-go/routing] To address this, multiple independent entities, one for each base station, play a crucial role in path selection while striving to optimize overall network performance.
[src:iris-go/routing] A 2003 measurement study of Internet routes found that, between pairs of neighboring ISPs, more than 30% of paths have inflated latency due to hot-potato routing, with 5% of paths being delayed by at least 12 ms.
[src:iris-go/routing] Inflation due to AS-level path selection, while substantial, was attributed primarily to BGP's lack of a mechanism to directly optimize for latency, rather than to selfish routing policies.
[src:iris-go/routing] It was also suggested that, were an appropriate mechanism in place, ISPs would be willing to cooperate to reduce latency rather than use hot-potato routing.
[src:iris-go/routing] Such a mechanism was later published by the same authors, first for the case of two ISPs and then for the global case.
[src:iris-go/routing] As the Internet and IP networks have become mission critical business tools, there has been increased interest in techniques and methods to monitor the routing posture of networks.
[src:iris-go/routing] Incorrect routing or routing issues cause undesirable performance degradation, flapping or downtime.
[src:iris-go/routing] Monitoring routing in a network is achieved using route analytics tools and techniques.
[src:iris-go/routing] In networks where a logically centralized control is available over the forwarding state, for example, using software-defined networking, routing techniques can be used that aim to optimize global and network-wide performance metrics.
[src:iris-go/routing] This has been used by large internet companies that operate many data centers in different geographical locations attached using private optical links, examples of which include Microsoft's Global WAN, Facebook's Express Backbone, and Google's B4.
[src:iris-go/routing] Global performance metrics to optimize include maximizing network utilization, minimizing traffic flow completion times, maximizing the traffic delivered prior to specific deadlines and reducing the completion times of flows.
[src:iris-go/routing] Work on the later over private WAN discusses modeling routing as a graph optimization problem by pushing all the queuing to the end-points.
[src:iris-go/routing] The authors also propose a heuristic to solve the problem efficiently while sacrificing negligible performance.
[src:iris-go/web-framework] A **web framework** (**WF**), **web application framework** (**WAF**), or **web development framework** is a software framework that is designed to support the development of web applications including web services, web resources, and web APIs.
[src:iris-go/web-framework] Web frameworks provide a standard way to build and deploy web applications on the World Wide Web.
[src:iris-go/web-framework] Web frameworks aim to automate the overhead associated with common activities performed in web development.
[src:iris-go/web-framework] For example, many web frameworks provide libraries for database access, templating frameworks, and session management, and they often promote code reuse.
[src:iris-go/web-framework] Although they often target development of dynamic web sites, they are also applicable to static websites.
[src:iris-go/web-framework] As the design of the World Wide Web was not inherently dynamic, early hypertext consisted of hand-coded HTML text files that were published on web servers.
[src:iris-go/web-framework] Any modifications to published pages needed to be performed by the pages' author.
[src:iris-go/web-framework] In 1993, the Common Gateway Interface (CGI) standard was introduced for interfacing external applications with web servers, to provide a dynamic web page that reflected user inputs.
[src:iris-go/web-framework] Original implementations of the CGI interface typically had adverse effects on the server load however, because each request started a separate process.
[src:iris-go/web-framework] More recent implementations utilize persistent processes amongst other techniques to reduce the footprint in the server's resources and offer a general performance boost.
[src:iris-go/web-framework] In 1995, fully integrated server/language development environments first emerged and new web-specific languages were introduced, such as ColdFusion, PHP, and Active Server Pages.
[src:iris-go/web-framework] Although the vast majority of languages for creating dynamic web pages have libraries to help with common tasks, web applications often require specific libraries for particular tasks, such as creating HTML (for example, Jakarta Faces).
[src:iris-go/web-framework] In the late 1990s, mature, "full stack" frameworks began to appear, that often gathered multiple libraries useful for web development into a single cohesive software stack for web developers to use.
[src:iris-go/web-framework] Most web frameworks are based on the model–view–controller (MVC) pattern.
[src:iris-go/web-framework] Many frameworks follow the MVC architectural pattern to separate the data model into business rules (the "controller") and the user interface (the "view").
[src:iris-go/web-framework] This is generally considered a good practice as it modularizes code, promotes code reuse, and allows multiple interfaces to be applied.
[src:iris-go/web-framework] In web applications, this permits different views to be presented, for example serving different web pages for mobile vs. desktop browsers, or providing machine-readable web service interfaces.
[src:iris-go/web-framework] Most MVC frameworks follow a push-based architecture also called "action-based".
[src:iris-go/web-framework] These frameworks use actions that do the required processing, and then "push" the data to the view layer to render the results.
[src:iris-go/web-framework] An alternative to this is pull-based architecture, sometimes also called "component-based".
[src:iris-go/web-framework] These frameworks start with the view layer, which can then "pull" results from multiple controllers as needed.
[src:iris-go/web-framework] In this architecture, multiple controllers can be involved with a single view.
[src:iris-go/web-framework] In three-tier organization, applications are structured around three physical tiers: client, application, and database.
[src:iris-go/web-framework] The application contains the business logic, running on a server and communicates with the client using HTTP.
[src:iris-go/web-framework] The client on web applications is a web browser that runs HTML generated by the application layer.
[src:iris-go/web-framework] The term should not be confused with MVC, where, unlike in three-tier architecture, it is considered a good practice to keep business logic away from the controller, the "middle layer".
[src:iris-go/web-framework] Web frameworks must function according to the architectural rules of browsers and protocols such as HTTP, which is stateless.
[src:iris-go/web-framework] Webpages are served up by a server and can then be modified by the browser using JavaScript.
[src:iris-go/web-framework] Either approach has its advantages and disadvantages.
[src:iris-go/web-framework] Server-side page changes typically require that the page be refreshed, but allow any language to be used and more computing power to be utilized.
[src:iris-go/web-framework] Client-side changes allow the page to be updated in small chunks which feels like a desktop application, but are limited to JavaScript and run in the user's browser, which may have limited computing power.
[src:iris-go/web-framework] Applications which make heavy use of JavaScript and only refresh parts of the page, are called single-page applications and typically make use of a client-side JavaScript web framework to organize the code.
[src:iris-go/web-framework] Examples include Backbone.js, AngularJS, Angular, Ember.js, ReactJS, jQuery UI, Svelte, and Vue.js.
[src:iris-go/web-framework] JavaScript-based web application frameworks, such as React and Vue, provide extensive capabilities but come with associated trade-offs.
[src:iris-go/web-framework] These frameworks often extend or enhance features available through native web technologies, such as routing, component-based development, and state management.
[src:iris-go/web-framework] Frameworks can introduce abstraction layers that may contribute to performance overhead, larger bundle sizes, and increased complexity.
[src:iris-go/web-framework] Modern frameworks, such as React 18 and Vue 3, address these challenges with features like concurrent rendering, tree-shaking, and selective hydration.
[src:iris-go/web-framework] While these advancements improve rendering efficiency and resource management, their benefits depend on the specific application and implementation context.
[src:iris-go/web-framework] Lightweight frameworks, such as Svelte and Preact, take different architectural approaches, with Svelte eliminating the virtual DOM entirely in favor of compiling components to efficient JavaScript code, and Preact offering a minimal, compatible alternative to React.
[src:iris-go/web-framework] Framework choice depends on an application’s requirements, including the team’s expertise, performance goals, and development priorities.
[src:iris-go/web-framework] A newer category of web frameworks, including enhance.dev, Astro, and Fresh, leverages native web standards while minimizing abstractions and development tooling.
[src:iris-go/web-framework] These solutions emphasize progressive enhancement, server-side rendering, and optimizing performance.
[src:iris-go/web-framework] Astro renders static HTML by default while hydrating only interactive parts.
[src:iris-go/web-framework] Fresh focuses on server-side rendering with zero runtime overhead.
[src:iris-go/web-framework] Enhance.dev prioritizes progressive enhancement patterns using Web Components.
[src:iris-go/web-framework] While these tools reduce reliance on client-side JavaScript by shifting logic to build-time or server-side execution, they still use JavaScript where necessary for interactivity.
[src:iris-go/web-framework] This approach makes them particularly suitable for performance-critical and content-focused applications.
[src:iris-go/web-framework] Frameworks typically set the control flow of a program and allow the user of the framework to "hook into" that flow by exposing various events.
[src:iris-go/web-framework] This "inversion of control" design pattern is considered to be a defining principle of a framework, and benefits the code by enforcing a common flow for a team which everyone can customize in similar ways.
[src:iris-go/web-framework] For example, some popular "microframeworks" such as Ruby's Sinatra (which inspired Express.js) allow for "middleware" hooks prior to and after HTTP requests.
[src:iris-go/web-framework] These middleware functions can be anything, and allow the user to define logging, authentication and session management, and redirecting.
[src:iris-go/web-framework] Web caching is the caching of web documents in order to reduce bandwidth usage, server load, and perceived "lag".
[src:iris-go/web-framework] A web cache stores copies of documents passing through it; subsequent requests may be satisfied from the cache if certain conditions are met.
[src:iris-go/web-framework] Some application frameworks provide mechanisms for caching documents and bypassing various stages of the page's preparation, such as database access or template interpretation.
[src:iris-go/web-framework] Some web frameworks come with authentication and authorization frameworks, that enable the web server to identify the users of the application, and restrict access to functions based on some defined criteria.
[src:iris-go/web-framework] Drupal is one example that provides role-based access to pages, and provides a web-based interface for creating users and assigning them roles.
[src:iris-go/web-framework] Many web frameworks create a unified API to a database backend, enabling web applications to work with a variety of databases with no code changes, and allowing programmers to work with higher-level concepts.
[src:iris-go/web-framework] Additionally, some object-oriented frameworks contain mapping tools to provide object-relational mapping, which maps objects to tuples.
[src:iris-go/web-framework] Some frameworks minimize web application configuration through the use of introspection and/or following well-known conventions.
[src:iris-go/web-framework] For example, many Java frameworks use Hibernate as a persistence layer, which can generate a database schema at runtime capable of persisting the necessary information.
[src:iris-go/web-framework] This allows the application designer to design business objects without needing to explicitly define a database schema.
[src:iris-go/web-framework] Frameworks such as Ruby on Rails can also work in reverse, that is, define properties of model objects at runtime based on a database schema.
[src:iris-go/web-framework] Other features web frameworks may provide include transactional support and database migration tools.
[src:iris-go/web-framework] A framework's URL mapping or routing facility is the mechanism by which the framework interprets URLs.
[src:iris-go/web-framework] Some frameworks, such as Drupal and Django, match the provided URL against pre-determined patterns using regular expressions, while some others use rewriting techniques to translate the provided URL into one that the underlying engine will recognize.
[src:iris-go/web-framework] Another technique is that of graph traversal such as used by Zope, where a URL is decomposed in steps that traverse an object graph (of models and views).
[src:iris-go/web-framework] A URL mapping system that uses pattern matching or rewriting to route and handle requests allows for shorter more "friendly URLs" to be used, increasing the simplicity of the site and allowing for better indexing by search engines.
[src:iris-go/web-framework] For example, a URL that ends with "/page.cgi?cat=science&topic=physics" could be changed to simply "/page/science/physics".
[src:iris-go/web-framework] This makes the URL easier for people to remember, read and write, and provides search engines with better information about the structural layout of the site.
[src:iris-go/web-framework] A graph traversal approach also tends to result in the creation of friendly URLs.
[src:iris-go/web-framework] A shorter URL such as "/page/science" tends to exist by default as that is simply a shorter form of the longer traversal to "/page/science/physics".
[src:iris-go/web-framework] Ajax, shorthand for "*Asynchronous JavaScript and XML*", is a web development technique for creating web applications.
[src:iris-go/web-framework] The intent is to make web pages feel more responsive by exchanging small amounts of data with the server behind the scenes, so that the entire web page does not have to be reloaded each time the user requests a change.
[src:iris-go/web-framework] This is intended to increase a web page's interactivity, speed, maintainability, and usability.
[src:iris-go/web-framework] Due to the complexity of Ajax programming in JavaScript, there are numerous Ajax frameworks that exclusively deal with Ajax support.
[src:iris-go/web-framework] Some Ajax frameworks are even embedded as a part of larger frameworks.
[src:iris-go/web-framework] For example, the jQuery JavaScript library is included in Ruby on Rails.
[src:iris-go/web-framework] With the increased interest in developing "Web 2.0" rich web applications, the complexity of programming directly in Ajax and JavaScript has become so apparent that compiler technology has stepped in, to allow developers to code in high-level languages such as Java, Python and Ruby.
[src:iris-go/web-framework] The first of these compilers was Morfik followed by Google Web Toolkit, with ports to Python and Ruby in the form of Pyjs and RubyJS following some time after.
[src:iris-go/web-framework] These compilers and their associated widget set libraries make the development of rich media Ajax applications much more akin to that of developing desktop applications.
[src:iris-go/web-framework] Some frameworks provide tools for creating and providing web services.
[src:iris-go/web-framework] These utilities may offer similar tools as the rest of the web application.
[src:iris-go/web-framework] A number of newer Web 2.0 RESTful frameworks are now providing resource-oriented architecture (ROA) infrastructure for building collections of resources in a sort of Semantic Web ontology, based on concepts from Resource Description Framework (RDF).
[src:iris-go/web-server-p01] A **web server** is computer software that accepts requests via HTTP (the network protocol created to distribute web content) or its secure variant HTTPS.
[src:iris-go/web-server-p01] A user agent, commonly a web browser or web crawler, initiates communication by making a request for a web page or other resource using HTTP, and the server responds with the content of that resource or an error message.
[src:iris-go/web-server-p01] A web server can also accept and store resources sent from the user agent if configured to do so.
[src:iris-go/web-server-p01] The hardware used to run a web server can vary according to the volume of requests that it needs to handle.
[src:iris-go/web-server-p01] At the low end of the range are embedded systems, such as a router that runs a small web server as its configuration interface.
[src:iris-go/web-server-p01] A high-traffic Internet website might handle requests with hundreds of servers that run on racks of high-speed computers.
[src:iris-go/web-server-p01] A resource sent from a web server can be a pre-existing file (static content) available to the web server, or it can be generated at the time of the request (dynamic content) by another program that communicates with the server software.
[src:iris-go/web-server-p01] The former usually can be served faster and can be more easily cached for repeated requests, while the latter supports a broader range of applications.
[src:iris-go/web-server-p01] Technologies such as REST and SOAP, which use HTTP as a basis for general computer-to-computer communication, as well as support for WebDAV extensions, have extended the application of web servers well beyond their original purpose of serving human-readable pages.
[src:iris-go/web-server-p01] In March 1989, Sir Tim Berners-Lee proposed a new project to his employer CERN, with the goal of easing the exchange of information between scientists by using a hypertext system.
[src:iris-go/web-server-p01] The proposal titled *"HyperText and CERN"*, asked for comments and it was read by several people.
[src:iris-go/web-server-p01] In October 1990 the proposal was reformulated and enriched (having as co-author Robert Cailliau), and finally, it was approved.
[src:iris-go/web-server-p01] Those early browsers retrieved web pages written in a simple early form of HTML from web servers using a new basic communication protocol that was named HTTP 0.9.
[src:iris-go/web-server-p01] In August 1991 Tim Berners-Lee announced the *birth of WWW technology* and encouraged scientists to adopt and develop it.
[src:iris-go/web-server-p01] Soon after, those programs, along with their source code, were made available to people interested in their usage.
[src:iris-go/web-server-p01] Although the source code was not formally licensed or placed in the public domain, CERN informally allowed users and developers to experiment and further develop on top of them.
[src:iris-go/web-server-p01] Berners-Lee started promoting the adoption and the usage of those programs along with their porting to other operating systems.
[src:iris-go/web-server-p01] In December 1991, the **first web server outside Europe** was installed at SLAC (U.S.A.).
[src:iris-go/web-server-p01] This was a very important event because it started trans-continental web communications between web browsers and web servers.
[src:iris-go/web-server-p01] In 1991–1993, CERN web server program continued to be actively developed by the www group, meanwhile, thanks to the availability of its source code and the public specifications of the HTTP protocol, many other implementations of web servers started to be developed.
[src:iris-go/web-server-p01] In April 1993, CERN issued a public official statement stating that the three components of Web software (the basic line-mode client, the web server and the library of common code), along with their source code, were put in the public domain.
[src:iris-go/web-server-p01] This statement freed web server developers from any possible legal issue about the development of *derivative work* based on that source code (a threat that in practice never existed).
[src:iris-go/web-server-p01] At the beginning of 1994, the most notable among new web servers was NCSA httpd which ran on a variety of Unix-based OSs and could serve *dynamically generated content* by implementing the `POST` HTTP method and the CGI to communicate with external programs.
[src:iris-go/web-server-p01] These capabilities, along with the multimedia features of NCSA's Mosaic browser (also able to manage HTML FORMs in order to send data to a web server) highlighted the potential of web technology for publishing and distributed computing applications.
[src:iris-go/web-server-p01] At the beginning of 1995 those patches were all applied to the last release of NCSA source code and, after several tests, the Apache HTTP server project was started.
[src:iris-go/web-server-p01] At the end of 1994, a new commercial web server, named Netsite, was released with specific features.
[src:iris-go/web-server-p01] It was the first one of many other similar products that were developed first by Netscape, then also by Sun Microsystems, and finally by Oracle Corporation.
[src:iris-go/web-server-p01] In mid-1995, the first version of IIS was released by Microsoft for Windows NT OS.
[src:iris-go/web-server-p01] This marked the entry, in the field of World Wide Web technologies, of a commercial developer and vendor that has played and still is playing a key role on both sides (client and server) of the web.
[src:iris-go/web-server-p01] In the second half of 1995, CERN and NCSA web servers started to decline (in global percentage usage) because of the widespread adoption of new web servers which had a much faster development cycle along with more features, more fixes applied, and more performances than the previous ones.
[src:iris-go/web-server-p01] At the end of 1996, there were already over fifty known, different web-server-software programs that were available to everybody who wanted to own an Internet domain name or to host websites.
[src:iris-go/web-server-p01] Many of them lived only shortly and were replaced by other web servers.
[src:iris-go/web-server-p01] The publication of RFCs about protocol versions HTTP/1.0 (1996) and HTTP/1.1 (1997, 1999), forced most web servers to comply (not always completely) with those standards.
[src:iris-go/web-server-p01] The use of TCP/IP persistent connections (HTTP/1.1) required web servers both to increase the maximum number of concurrent connections allowed and to improve their level of scalability.
[src:iris-go/web-server-p01] Between 1996 and 1999, Netscape Enterprise Server and Microsoft's IIS emerged among the leading commercial options whereas among the freely available and open-source programs Apache HTTP Server held the lead as the preferred server (because of its reliability and its many features).
[src:iris-go/web-server-p01] In those years there was also another commercial web server called Zeus (*now discontinued*) that was known as one of the fastest and most scalable web servers available on market, at least till the first decade of 2000s, despite its low percentage of usage.
[src:iris-go/web-server-p01] Apache resulted in the most used web server from mid-1996 to the end of 2015 when, after a few years of decline, it was surpassed initially by IIS and then by Nginx.
[src:iris-go/web-server-p01] Afterward IIS dropped to much lower percentages of usage than Apache (see also market share).
[src:iris-go/web-server-p01] From 2005–2006, Apache started to improve its speed and its scalability level by introducing new performance features (e.g., event MPM and new content cache).
[src:iris-go/web-server-p01] A few years after 2000 started, not only other commercial and highly competitive web servers (e.g., LiteSpeed) but also many other open-source programs such as Hiawatha, Cherokee HTTP server, Lighttpd, Nginx and other derived and related products also available with commercial support emerged.
[src:iris-go/web-server-p01] Within a year, these changes, on average, nearly tripled the maximum number of persistent connections that web servers had to manage.
[src:iris-go/web-server-p01] In 2015, RFCs published new protocol version [HTTP/2], and as the implementation of new specifications was not trivial at all, a **dilemma arose among developers of less popular web servers** (e.g., with a percentage of usage lower than 1% ..
[src:iris-go/web-server-p01] 2%), about adding or not adding support for that new protocol version.
[src:iris-go/web-server-p01] In 2020–2021 the HTTP/2 dynamics about its implementation (by top web servers and popular web browsers) were partly replicated after the publication of advanced drafts of future RFC about HTTP/3 protocol.
[src:iris-go/web-server-p01] The following technical overview should be considered only as an attempt to give a few very *limited examples* about *some* features that may be implemented in a web server and *some* of the tasks that it may perform in order to have a sufficiently wide scenario about the topic.
[src:iris-go/web-server-p01] A **web server program** plays the role of a server in a client–server model by implementing one or more versions of HTTP protocol, often including the HTTPS secure variant and other features and extensions that are considered useful for its planned usage.
[src:iris-go/web-server-p01] Although web server programs differ in how they are implemented, most of them offer the following common features.
[src:iris-go/web-server-p01] These are **basic features** that most web servers usually have.
[src:iris-go/web-server-p01] A few other more **advanced** and popular **features** (*only a very short selection*) are the following ones.
[src:iris-go/web-server-p01] Once an HTTP request message has been decoded and verified, its values can be used to determine whether that request can be satisfied or not.
[src:iris-go/web-server-p01] This requires many other steps, including **security checks**.
[src:iris-go/web-server-p01] The term *URL normalization* refers to the process of modifying and standardizing a URL in a consistent manner.
[src:iris-go/web-server-p01] There are several types of normalization that may be performed, including the conversion of the scheme and host to lowercase.
[src:iris-go/web-server-p01] Among the most important normalizations are the removal of "." and ".." path segments and adding trailing slashes to a non-empty path component.
[src:iris-go/web-server-p01] One or more configuration files of web server may specify the mapping of parts of **URL path** (e.g., initial parts of file path, filename extension and other path components) to a specific URL handler (file, directory, external program or internal module).
[src:iris-go/web-server-p01] Web server programs are able to translate an URL path (all or part of it), that refers to a physical file system path, to an absolute path under the target website's root directory.
[src:iris-go/web-server-p01] Website's root directory may be specified by a configuration file or by some internal rule of the web server by using the name of the website which is the host part of the URL found in HTTP client request.
[src:iris-go/web-server-p01] The web server appends the path found in requested URL (HTTP request message) and appends it to the path of the (Host) website root directory.
[src:iris-go/web-server-p01] On an Apache server, this is commonly `/home/www/website` (on Unix machines, usually it is: `/var/www/website`).
[src:iris-go/web-server-p01] See the following examples of how it may result.
[src:iris-go/web-server-p01] The web server then reads the file, if it exists, and sends a response to the client's web browser.
[src:iris-go/web-server-p01] The response will describe the content of the file and contain the file itself or an error message will return saying that the file does not exist or its access is forbidden.
[src:iris-go/web-server-p01] The response will describe the content of the directory (list of contained subdirectories and files) or an error message will return saying that the directory does not exist or its access is forbidden.
[src:iris-go/web-server-p01] For a *dynamic request* the URL path specified by the client should refer to an existing external program (usually an executable file with a CGI) used by the web server to generate dynamic content.
[src:iris-go/web-server-p01] The web server executes that program, passing in the path-info and the query string `action=view&orderby=thread&date=2021-10-15` so that the program has the info it needs to run.
[src:iris-go/web-server-p01] (In this case, it will return an HTML document containing a view of forum entries ordered by thread from October 15, 2021).
[src:iris-go/web-server-p01] In addition to this, the web server reads data sent from the external program and resends that data to the client that made the request.
[src:iris-go/web-server-p01] Once a request has been read, interpreted, and verified, it has to be managed depending on its method, its URL, and its parameters, which may include values of HTTP headers.
[src:iris-go/web-server-p01] That kind of content is called *static* because usually it is not changed by the web server when it is sent to clients and because it remains the same until it is modified (file modification) by some program.
[src:iris-go/web-server-p01] Response of static file content can be sped up by a **file cache**.
[src:iris-go/web-server-p01] Most used names for static index files are: `index.html`, `index.htm` and `Default.htm`.
[src:iris-go/web-server-p01] If a web server program receives a client request message with an URL whose path matches the file name of an existing *file* and that file is accessible by web server program and its attributes match internal rules of web server program, then web server program can send that file to client.
[src:iris-go/web-server-p01] Usually, for security reasons, most web server programs are pre-configured to serve only regular files or to avoid to use *special file types* like device files, along with symbolic links or hard links to them.
[src:iris-go/web-server-p01] The aim is to avoid undesirable side effects when serving static web resources.
[src:iris-go/web-server-p01] If a web server program is capable of **serving dynamic content** and it has been configured to do so, then it is able to communicate with the proper internal module or external program (associated with the requested URL path) in order to pass to it the parameters of the client request.
[src:iris-go/web-server-p01] After that, the web server program reads from it its data response (that it has generated, often on the fly) and then it resends it to the client program who made the request.
[src:iris-go/web-server-p01] In order to be able to communicate with its internal modules or external programs, a web server program must have implemented one or more of the many available **gateway interfaces** (see also Web Server Gateway Interfaces used for dynamic content).
[src:iris-go/web-server-p01] The three **standard** and historical **gateway interfaces** are the following ones.
[src:iris-go/web-server-p01] An external CGI program is run by web server program for each dynamic request, then web server program reads from it the generated data response and then resends it to client.
[src:iris-go/web-server-p01] An external FastCGI program (it usually is a process) is started once by web server program or by some other program or process and then it waits for a network connection which is established permanently by web server; through that connection are sent the request parameters and read data responses.
[src:iris-go/web-server-p01] A web server program may be capable to manage the dynamic generation (on the fly) of a **directory index list** of files and sub-directories.
[src:iris-go/web-server-p01] If it cannot be generated an error is returned.
[src:iris-go/web-server-p01] Usage of dynamically generated *directory listings* is usually avoided or limited to a few selected directories of a website because that generation takes much more OS resources than sending a static index page.
[src:iris-go/web-server-p01] The main usage of *directory listings* is to allow the download of files (usually when their names, sizes, modification date-times or file attributes may change randomly and frequently) *as they are, without requiring to provide further information to requesting user*.
[src:iris-go/web-server-p01] In practice whenever there is content that may vary, depending on one or more parameters contained in client request or in configuration settings, then, usually, it is generated dynamically.
[src:iris-go/web-server-p01] Web server programs are able to send response messages as replies to client request messages.
[src:iris-go/web-server-p01] An error response message may be sent because a request message could not be successfully read or decoded or analyzed or executed.
[src:iris-go/web-server-p01] NOTE: the following sections are reported only as examples to help to understand what a web server, more or less, does; these sections are by any means neither exhaustive nor complete.
[src:iris-go/web-server-p01] When an error response or message is received by a client browser, then if it is related to the main user request (e.g., an URL of a web resource such as a web page) then usually that error message is shown in some browser window or message.
[src:iris-go/web-server-p01] Example 1: a URL path points to a **directory** name but it does not have a final slash '/' so web server sends a redirect to client in order to instruct it to redo the request with the fixed path name.
[src:iris-go/web-server-p01] Example 2: a whole set of documents has been **moved inside website** in order to reorganize their file system paths.
[src:iris-go/web-server-p01] Example 3: a whole set of documents has been **moved to a new website** and now it is mandatory to use secure HTTPS connections to access them.
[src:iris-go/web-server-p01] Above examples are only a few of the possible kind of redirections.
[src:iris-go/web-server-p01] A web server program is able to reply to a valid client request message with a successful message, optionally containing requested **web resource data**.
[src:iris-go/web-server-p01] If web resource data is sent back to client, then it can be **static content** or **dynamic content** depending on how it has been retrieved (from a file or from the output of some program or module).
[src:iris-go/web-server-p01] In order to speed up web server responses by lowering average HTTP response times and hardware resources used, many popular web servers implement one or more content caches, each one specialized in a content category.
[src:iris-go/web-server-p01] In practice, nowadays, many web server programs include their own *userland* **file cache**, tailored for a web server usage and using their specific implementation and parameters.
[src:iris-go/web-server-p01] The wide spread adoption of RAID and fast solid-state drives (storage hardware with very high I/O speed) has slightly reduced but of course not eliminated the advantage of having a file cache incorporated in a web server.
[src:iris-go/web-server-p01] Dynamic content, output by an internal module or an external program, may not always change very frequently (given a unique URL with keys or parameters) and so, maybe for a while (e.g., from one second to several hours or more), the resulting output can be cached in RAM or even on a fast disk.
[src:iris-go/web-server-p01] Anyway, in most cases those kind of caches are implemented by external servers (e.g., reverse proxy) or by storing dynamic data output in separate computers, managed by specific applications (e.g., memcached), in order to not compete for hardware resources (CPU, RAM, disks) with web servers.
[src:iris-go/web-server-p01] A web server software can be either incorporated into the OS and executed in kernel space, or it can be executed in user space (like other regular applications).
[src:iris-go/web-server-p01] Web servers that run in user-mode have to ask the system for permission to use more memory or more CPU resources.
[src:iris-go/web-server-p01] Not only do these requests to the kernel take time, but they might not always be satisfied because the system reserves resources for its own usage and has the responsibility to share hardware resources with all the other running applications.
[src:iris-go/web-server-p01] Executing in user mode can also mean using more buffer or data copies (between user-space and kernel-space) which can lead to a decrease in the performance of a user-mode web server.
[src:iris-go/web-server-p01] Nowadays almost all web server software is executed in user mode (because many of the aforementioned small disadvantages have been overcome by faster hardware, new OS versions, much faster OS system calls and new optimized web server software).
[src:iris-go/web-server-p01] See also comparison of web server software to discover which of them run in kernel mode or in user mode (also referred as kernel space or user space).
[src:iris-go/web-server-p01] In other words, a **web server should always be very responsive**, even under high load of web traffic, in order to keep **total user's wait** (sum of browser time + network time + **web server response time**) for a response **as low as possible**.
[src:iris-go/web-server-p01] Among the operating conditions, the **number** (1 ..
[src:iris-go/web-server-p01] *n*) of **concurrent client connections** used during a test is an important parameter because it allows to correlate the **concurrency level** supported by web server with results of the tested performance metrics.
[src:iris-go/web-server-p01] ... used to implement a web server program, **can bias a lot the performances** and in particular the **scalability level** that can be achieved under **heavy load** or when using high end hardware (many CPUs, disks and lots of RAM).
[src:iris-go/web-server-p01] In practice some web server software models may require more OS resources (specially more CPUs and more RAM) than others to be able to work well and so to achieve target performances.
[src:iris-go/web-server-p01] Performances of a web server are typically benchmarked by using one or more of the available automated load testing tools.
[src:iris-go/web-server-p02] When a web server is near to or over its load limits, it gets **overloaded** and so it may become **unresponsive**.
[src:iris-go/web-server-p02] Below are the latest statistics of the market share of all sites of the top web servers on the Internet by Netcraft.
[src:iris-go/web-server-p02] NOTE: (*) percentage rounded to integer number, because its decimal values are not publicly reported by source page (only its rounded value is reported in graph).
